Date: 0/0/1883
Source: Ranolf and Amohia
Author: DOMETT
Vol / Page: 2/63
Edition:
Quote: A couch for two, fenced all around/ [64] With aromatic <i> leptosperm </i> - -->[get Domett reference] Ma'nuka .... O. Myrtaceae; G. Leptospermum; S. or L. ericoides. `A large shrub or small tree; leaves used as tea in Tasmania and Australia, where the plant is equally abundant.' In the poem it is called indiscriminately manuka, broom, broom-like myrtle, or leptosperm. The settlers often call it `tea-broom.'
